// ch03: "`T&`/`const T&` -- reuses real C++ reference syntax." Real C++
// allows a `const T&` parameter to bind directly to a temporary (a
// literal constant, or any other rvalue), extending the temporary's
// lifetime for the call -- a common, idiomatic pattern
// (`f(42)` for `void f(const int& x)`). This is currently rejected: a
// reference "can currently only borrow a plain local variable, a field
// of one, an array element of one, a dereferenced
// std::unique_ptr/raw-pointer local, or the result of a call to a
// reference-returning function -- not an arbitrary expression"
// (confirmed to include a bare literal). Passing a named local variable
// instead works fine (see writing_through_const_reference_parameter_is_
// rejected.scpp and others in this category, all of which happen to
// only ever pass named locals).
int f(const int& x) {
    int y = x;
    return y;
}

int main() {
    return f(42);
}
